The latest intelligence reports from within Ukraine suggest Vladimir Putin's forces are moving on Kyiv. The country's capital hosts the central government headed by President Volodymyr Zelenskiy, who fears Russian squads are advancing on his position. Should Kyiv fall, Russia would gain a territory bordering several NATO members bound by policy to protect one another. Allied nations formed NATO in 1949 via the postwar North Atlantic Treaty. The treaty bound the UK with the then Western Union, US, Canada, Portugal, Italy, Norway, Denmark and Iceland. Over the years, it has blossomed into a vast network of countries offering mutual protection, with 30 now in its ranks. READ MORE:Â Polish MEP bemoans that no-one in EU as strong as Boris against Putin Current NATO members include: NATO also operates with a host of "partners" and international organisations without member or aspirational status. These include nations within the Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council (EAPC) and Istanbul Cooperation Initiative (ICI) and several countries outside these organisations. While not members, they may cooperate on mutual interests such as defence. EAPC countries include: ICI nations include: The following countries are part of NATO's "Mediterranean Dialogue": NATO also has "partners across the globe" that include: